s representing communities about to be replaced by one which elevates numbers above community. Advanced under the slogan of ‘making votes equal’, this new regime promises fairness yet, as the authors show, is destined to fail to address the disproportional and biased election results that have long been a feature of UK politics.Concluding with a detailed consideration of the ways in which various parts of the UK have embraced alternatives to first-past-the-post over the last two decades, this book serves as a timely reminder that the needs of political parties do not always coincide with those of us, the electors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectionszGreat Britain. 0aRepresentative government and representationzGreat Britain. 70(DE-588)4044696-70(DE-627)1062045990(DE-576)209061987aParlamentarismus2gnd 70(DE-588)4049535-80(DE-627)1061866040(DE-576)209082496aRepräsentative Demokratie2gnd 70(DE-588)4139210-30(DE-627)1056370760(DE-576)209692480aWahlsystem2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aBoundary commissions.  aConstituencies.  aDisproportionality and bias.  aElectoral equality.  aElectoral reform.  aElectoral systems.  aFirst-past-the-post.  aGeography.  aRepresentative democracy.  aVotes to seats.1 aJohnston, Ron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPattie, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPattie, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRossiter, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRossiter, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.or